\par \pard\plain \s4\sb120\sa120\keepn\b\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\ab\loch\f3\fs24{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Overview}
\par \pard\plain \s24\sb0\sa283{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
A simple programming language is provided for easily writing portable algorithms to be transpiled to and used by programs in other languages. The name "StageL" comes from calling it a "staging language" (which refers to its being a tool for developing the main EITE software, which should provide a more complete language).}{
{\*\atnid }{\*\atnauthor }\chatn{\*\annotation{\*\atndate -2022058602}\ltrpar\rtlch \ltrch\loch{\langfe1023\alang1023\dbch\af11\dbch\af11\lang1023
Also, "StageL" sounds catchy, and should be relatively easy to search for. It does seem reminiscent of "stage left" in theater, but that doesn't really have anything to do with it.}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 This project was inspired by the ugly code that resulted when I tried to write using these principles directly in JavaScript, needing a lot of easy-to-mess-up boilerplate code and awkward notation (largely because it is not strongly typed).}
\par \pard\plain \s4\sb120\sa120\keepn\b\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\ab\loch\f3\fs24{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Design goals}
\par \pard\plain \s24\sb0\sa283{\listtext\pard\plain \dbch\af7\dbch\af7\loch\f7 \u8226\'95\tab}\ilvl0\ls18 \li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi-283\tx707\li707\ri0\lin707\rin0\fi-283\sb0\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Imperative language. Trivial to implement, learn, and read; extremely portable. }
\par \pard\plain \s24\sb0\sa283{\listtext\pard\plain \dbch\af7\dbch\af7\loch\f7 \u8226\'95\tab}\ilvl0\ls18 \li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi-283\tx707\li707\ri0\lin707\rin0\fi-283\sb0\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Provide function calls, arrays, strings, numbers, booleans, and operators for these types with strict typing. Objects and first-class functions are out of scope for this language. (It's closer to duck-typed in practice, as e.g. in Bash there would be no distinction between string 0 and number 0.) }
